An open letter to changing names.

Dear John Green.
No, sweden did not have 12 kings named Charles. It had 12 kings named Karl. Or Carl. Or latinized to Carolus. His full title was:
Carl med Guds Nåde, Sveriges, Götes och Vendes Konung, Storfurste till Finland, Hertig uti Skåne, Estland, Livland, Karelen, Bremen, Verden, Stettin, Pommern, Kassuben och Venden, Furste till Rügen, Herre över Ingermanland och Wismar, så ock Pfalzgreve vid Rhen, i Bayern, samt till Jülich, Kleve och Berg Hertig. Greve till Valdens, Spanheim, Mark och Ravensburg och Herre till Ravenstein.
Translated that is:
Carl with the Grace of God, king of Sweden, Göte and Vende, Grand duke of Finland, Duke of Skåne, Estland, Livland, Karelen, Bremen, Verden, Stettin, Pommern, Kassuben and Venden, Duke of Rügen, Lord over Ingermanland and Wismar, and so Pfalzgreve by Rhen, in Bayern, also to Jülich, Kleve and Berg Duke. Count to Valdens, Spanheim, Mark and Ravensburg and Lord of Ravenstein.

And no, i do not concede that Charles is the English was of saying Carl. Why you get to do that is beyond me. Its like we here in Sweden were to pronounce Donald Trump as Kalle Trump (because we for some reason renamed Donald Duck into Kalle Anka, so i guess the same rules applies here).
Its simply rude to change names because of silly reasons. Is it hard to pronounce? No. even if it was it is up to you to make the effort.
Your name is after all John Green, and not John Grin, Jon Grön or Johan Grän, right? That would simply be to fail in saying your name. And so should it also be with historical figures to the extent its possible. Hirohito should not be renamed Henningway because it sounds more english or american.

From Sweden with love
- Kami

a Bit Short on Prussia, but it really mostly just did what the others did. I did miss some tidbits though.
Brandenburg lost around 2/3 it's Population in the 30 years war, the prince elector was family wise close to both Poland-Lithuanian and Sweden, he hot the rights to the Prussian lands via intermarriage, but he got the rights to actually rule in it by Poland-Lithuania as they hoped Brandenburg to be an ally against the Swedes. Then after the war, he did want a huge army, which he couldn't convince the general-Estates to give him more money, so he did something revolutionary, he send out his own tax collectors which were so harsh that they impoverished the population even more. And once the fighting was over, another revolutionary thing happened, both army and tax-collectors staid, and the push back was not great enough to stop it. All the new state-organization was ONLY there to make the way-to-big Army work. That's why Voltair said that Prussia was an Army with a State.
Then King Frederik the 3rd wanted an even larger army, it went so far (and was so lucrative for recruiters), that there had to be special Edicts in place that limited the age boys could be enrolled, and people could go back and do work for their family after 2 years of training, as well as letting soldiers do work for pay (which also had to be stopped via some edics when actual war happened). The large Army did make manufactures more popular, as now a large amount of similar goods were needed.

The History of Brandenburg/Prussia and the Hohenzollern is by far not a glorious one, in just about any aspect outside of how often a ruler-family can undeservedly roll a 20 in a row.

Some facts you may find interesting about Russia during Peter's reign:
1. During the first battle of Narva Russian army was betrayed by its foreign officers: there were just not enough literate Russian nobles, so a lot of English, Scottish, Polish and even Swedish mercenaries were recruited.
2. Russian recruits in many cases couldn't tell left and right apart, so drill instructors had to strap hay and straw to their boots. Instead of "Left, right, left, right..." They marched like "hay, straw, hay, straw!"
3. When Peter found out his closest friend count Menshikov stole state money instead of buying new uniforms, he beat him with his own fists during diplomatic negotiations. And he was considered lucky as other corrupted officials were hanged for such crimes.
4. Saint Petersburg people had to pay their taxes in stones for some time in order to pave the roads of the city. So many peasants died during it's first years it was said to be standing "on bones".
5. After the defeat of Narva Russia lost almost all of its artillery and there was not enough copper to make new guns. Peter ordered to take church bells off and melt them. while peter is a very important historical figure and modernizer, the entire russian state was gradually reforming and taking on the best practices of the time (which were european ones thanks to you know, renaissance and age of discovery and all that). for example, the first russian military units taught in the ways of 17th century european warfare formed in 1640's. The first institution of higher learning (essentially a university except in name) formed in the 1680's, and foreigners have had a sizable presence in Moscow since Ivan the terrible. Peter the Great was successful in formalizing these changes and implementing them amongst all of nobility. Some do make a pretty convincing argument that his reforms may have been needlessly intrusive and that things were heading in that direction regardless. Obviously this is all very nuanced history that you don't have time to cram into a 10 minute video, but I thought I'd give some insight into some of the modern academic debate surrounding the figure of peter the great. While you may be disappointed to learn that Sweden had NOT in fact had 12 kings named Charles by that point, it is actually pretty interesting that our FIRST king named Charles was Charles VII. Charles I through VI were made up by a 15th century historian, probably to give a bit of old-timey prestige to the name.

Also, none of them were named Charles. They were all named Karl, but for some reason we and the rest of the world have an agreement to rename each other's kings specifically. So English history books get his name wrong, but don't worry, according to Swedish history books England has never had a king named Henry, William, John or Charles. And no country in the world has ever been ruled by a "Louis". That would just be ridiculous.
